                    <h3>Origin of the Idea</h3>
                    <p class="fst-italic" style="font-size:18px">
                        Life insurance constitutes a significant segment of the world’s insurance business.
                    </p>

                    <ul style="font-weight:bold">
                        <li><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i>Every year, some 100 million people worldwide are forced into poverty by health care costs.</li>
                        <li><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i>In 2020, 8.6 percent of people, or 28.0 million, did not have health insurance at any point during the year.</li>
                        <li><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i>The insurance penetration rate of one of the developing countries recorded at just 3.76% of the GDP as “extremely low” against comparable developed countries for FY21. </li>
                        <li><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i>These low penetrations reveal the uninsured nature of large sections of the population in such developing countries and the presence of an insurance gap. </li>
                        <li><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i>Lacking health insurance-related knowledge and skills—or health insurance literacy—puts people at risk of choosing an insurance product that could fail to provide needed benefits or protect them financially. </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p class="fst-italic" style="font-size:18px">
                        With the advent of the COVID-19 outbreak, the pandemic has had an outsized impact on life insurance returns in 2020 relative to the overall market.
                        The current premium determination is based on pre-defined parameters such as historic data, age, gender, and region.  High and constant standard Premium is one of the main reasons people avoid health/life insurance.
                    </p>
                </div>
